FOODBORNE OUTBREAK - ITALY (TURIN) (02)
=======================================
[see
Foodborne outbreak - Italy (Turin) 970521220637]
Date: Thu, 22 May 1997 10:10:07 -0800
From: varmint@well.com (Hacsi Horvath)
An update on the situation in Turin, forwarded from the foodsafe listserve.
---
Hacsi Horvath
***
Date: Thu, 22 May 1997 15:15:12 +0200
To: foodsafe@nal.usda.gov
From: massimo tarditi <arclab@inrete.it>
Subject: foodborne outbreak in Turin - 2nd message
Update (up to 22 may 1:00 p.m) about the toxi-infestion episode:
People involved are more than 1000 children in schools of Moncalieri and
Giaveno, near Torino. Between them are 25 childrens from Chernobyl
(Ukraine), hosted by Italian families in Giaveno. In the morning of 22 May
also 15 students of university had similar symptoms.
450 children spent the night at many hospitals around Turin; 300 are still
in hospital. Symptoms include fever, abdominal cramps, vertigins, fever, not
diarrhea (as reported by television first time).
Microbiological analyses are started in the evening of May 21 on foods
sampled in the Sogerco plant in Borgaro (TO) by police and inspectors of
Public Health Service.
In the schools, food consumed were: 20 may - 00:30 p.m.: canned tuna and
canned maize salad; carrots (raw) salad with lemon; bread; pasta with olive
oil; fruits. Canned tuna is imported from Spain. 21 may breakfast (8,30
a.m.): yoghurt with fruits. Foods are prepared in Borgaro and carried by
vehicle to schools (30-40 Km far). 17 schools in Moncalieri and 6 schools in
Giaveno are involved.
First symptoms beginning at 10:00 a.m. 21 may, up to 2:00 p.m. (as reported
by "La Stampa" journal.
First results are waited by evening of May 22.
---
Massimo Tarditi, Biologist
Studio Associato Arclab - 10043 Orbassano (TO) - Italy - Strada Torino 49
Microbiological and chemical analysis of foods, water, cosmetics.
Consultancy on food hygiene for food producers.
Laboratory acknowledged by Italian Ministry of Health
Consultant of the Law-court
